                                         "text":  "### Cosmic Microwave Background\n\nThe image in this section shows the Cosmic Microwave Background (CMB) recorded by the ESA (European Space Agency) Planck mission (<htcite0>).\n\n#### It is not noise, it is a discovery\n\nIn <htdate0>, A. A. Penzias and R. W. Wilson observed that the temperature of a horn reflector antenna remained 3.5 K (Kelvin) higher than expected (<htcite1>).",
                                         "source":  [
                                                        {
                                                            "type":  0,
                                                            "uuid":  "6006cb3a-9409-4d2a-999c-e4c74249f563",
                                                            "text":  "ESA",
                                                            "page":  "",
                                                            "date_time":  {
                                                                              "type":  "gregory",
                                                                              "year":  "",
                                                                              "month":  "-1",
                                                                              "day":  "-1"
                                                                          }
                                                        },
                                                        {
                                                            "type":  1,
                                                            "uuid":  "587cdba4-cefb-4df9-8514-2e50ccf88739",
                                                            "text":  "Penzias, A. A., & Wilson, R. W.",
                                                            "page":  "pp. 419 - 420",
                                                            "date_time":  {
                                                                              "type":  "gregory",
                                                                              "year":  "1965",
                                                                              "month":  "-1",
                                                                              "day":  "-1"
                                                                          }
                                                        }
                                                    ],
                                         "date_time":  null,
                                         "isTable":  false,
                                         "imgdesc":  "",
                                         "format":  "markdown",
                                         "PostMention":  ""
                                     },
                                     {
                                         "text":  "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: What could it be?</b><br /><br />When we talk about measuring temperature, we usually think of a thermometer. Imagine that you feel fine, no fever, but when you take your temperature, the thermometer reads 40 °C.<br /><br />What would you do in that situation?</div></div></center></p>",
                                         "source":  [

                                                    ],
                                         "date_time":  null,
                                         "isTable":  false,
                                         "imgdesc":  "",
                                         "format":  "markdown",
                                         "PostMention":  ""
                                     },
                                     {
                                         "text":  "You would probably suspect that there is something wrong with the thermometer. Similarly, the researchers also tested for potential problems.\n\nWhile investigating possible measurement errors, Penzias and Wilson ruled out a series of potential causes: atmospheric absorption, impedance, antenna temperature, imperfections in the structure, and even backlobe effects (<htcite0>).\n\nWith all instrumental problems eliminated, the need to find a new explanation arose.\n\n### Confirming the Big Bang\n\nThe measurements by Penzias and Wilson could not be attributed to any known source in the Universe—such as stars or galaxies (<htcite1>). However, their results matched the predictions presented in another paper, by R. H. Dicke, P. J. E. Peebles, P. G. Roll, and D. T. Wilkinson (<htcite2>; <htcite3>).\n\nAccording to Dicke et al., the early Universe should have had a temperature of about 10 billion Kelvin (10,000,000,000 K), which, throughout the cosmic expansion, would have cooled to approximately 3.5 K—exactly the value observed by Penzias and Wilson (<htcite4>).\n\nThis discovery not only confirmed the prediction of the Cosmic Microwave Background but also reinforced the model of a uniform and isotropic Universe—that is, with the same properties in all directions of space (<htcite5>; <htcite6>).",
                                         "source":  [
